    <h3>Our Approach</h3>
    <p>The approach that has emerged from the CodeX Community can be summarized along five tracks that typically overlap in time and evolve with experience:</p>
    <p><%= image_tag '5_steps.png', :width => '100%', :class => 'py-5' %></p>

    <ol class="section-list">
      <li><%= link_to("Community Building", "community.html") %>, including committed leadership with a broad reach; a fair and sustainable governance framework; and a growing group of diverse participants and skillsets. Certain organizations and skills are typically needed only at certain points in the work. </li>
      <li><%= link_to("Use Cases & Planning", "use_cases_planning.html") %>, including prioritizing Use Cases (specific challenges, proposed new work and data flows); organizing and scheduling work right through to adoption and measuring value; and securing the resources (organizations, people/skills) needed to succeed. Specific Use Cases attract specific subsets of each specialty.</li>
      <li><%= link_to("Standards Development", "standards.html") %>, based on compiling clinical experts’ requirements to address Use Cases; incorporating these into HL7 Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources Implementation Guides (FHIR IGs) – increasingly demanded and required for data exchange) – based on a set of design principles considered during the development of mCODE;  and standardizing, updating (based on experience), and maintaining the FHIR IGs within Health Level Seven (HL7).</li>
      <li><%= link_to("Implementation & Testing", "implementation.html") %> Implementation of the FHIR IG(s) into systems (generally commercial) and workflows; Testing of systems and workflows within the types organizations ultimately planned to host, use, and benefit from the work; and feedback from testing to update Planning and Standards work, and to eventually demonstrate potential value of the work. These demonstrations often attract additional participants to the Community.</li>
      <li><%= link_to("Adoption & Value", "adoption.html") %> in the real world is best driven by understanding at the Planning track what factors will move the market – including user demands, Government mandates, quality standards, and hopefully the promise of improved care and research during testing. It’s critical to Measure such improvements in the real world, to see where changes could make solutions even better (quality, cost, time) and help other participants engage.</li>
    </ol>
    



